1
00:03:01,780 --> 00:03:06,040
I was born in the Soviet Union in '58.

2
00:03:06,040 --> 00:03:09,620
It was 13 years after
World War II was over.

3
00:03:09,680 --> 00:03:12,960
The whole country was ruined.

4
00:03:13,020 --> 00:03:15,430
We lost 20 million people.

5
00:03:15,490 --> 00:03:16,920
It's a lot.

6
00:03:17,230 --> 00:03:19,710
We was living in Stalin's buildings.

7
00:03:19,760 --> 00:03:23,180
Probably a 400 square foot apartment.

8
00:03:23,180 --> 00:03:27,110
No running water,
no toilets, three families.

9
00:03:27,170 --> 00:03:30,240
It was a pretty rough lifestyle.

10
00:03:31,940 --> 00:03:34,280
I was a happy kid.

11
00:03:35,110 --> 00:03:38,060
I play a game. I play hockey.

12
00:03:49,260 --> 00:03:51,870
Pucks was empty cans and stuff like that.

13
00:03:51,870 --> 00:03:53,830
But, we had fun.

14
00:03:56,660 --> 00:04:00,610
Our heroes played for the
Red Army Club, for the national team.

15
00:04:15,980 --> 00:04:16,990
Vladimir Pozner
Journalist

16
00:04:23,860 --> 00:04:25,360
TRYOUTS!

17
00:04:28,360 --> 00:04:30,470
JOIN THE RED ARMY HOCKEY TEAM
AND SERVE YOUR COUNTRY.

18
00:04:31,730 --> 00:04:34,650
My mom and dad,
they probably collected for two years.

19
00:04:34,700 --> 00:04:39,910
They bought for me gloves,
helmet, and the skates.

20
00:04:39,970 --> 00:04:43,840
On the black market,
it probably cost 250 rubles.

21
00:04:44,080 --> 00:04:47,220
It was big money for a Soviet family.

22
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:04,470
There was a huge line of the boys

23
00:05:04,530 --> 00:05:06,410
With the sticks. With the skates.

24
00:05:06,600 --> 00:05:09,070
With the parents. With the grandparents.

25
00:05:09,070 --> 00:05:13,540
It's unbelievable.
It's probably 3-4 miles long.

26
00:05:42,800 --> 00:05:44,750
I was 9 years old.

27
00:05:44,810 --> 00:05:47,780
I stayed in line probably 7 or 8 hours.

28
00:05:48,010 --> 00:05:50,080
I was exhausted.

29
00:05:50,070 --> 00:05:52,420
I got no chance.

30
00:05:52,480 --> 00:05:56,760
They said, "Thank you very much.
Come again next year."

31
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:00,230
So I practiced 3 or 4 times a day.

32
00:06:11,230 --> 00:06:15,610
Finally, they said I was good
enough to make the team.

33
00:06:15,670 --> 00:06:19,810
I was so proud to play for Red Army.

34
00:07:04,690 --> 00:07:07,930
<i>Skate with no fear.{\i}</i>

35
00:07:07,990 --> 00:07:12,410
<i>We'll give you exercises
no one has ever seen.{\i}</i>

36
00:07:12,410 --> 00:07:14,970
<i>You'll be juggling your sticks,{\i}</i>

37
00:07:16,360 --> 00:07:20,160
<i>twisting them around your head.{\i}</i>

38
00:07:22,040 --> 00:07:26,800
<i>Where's the smile? You're playing hockey!{\i}</i>

39
00:07:27,340 --> 00:07:29,130
<i>Jump! Quick!{\i}</i>

40
00:07:31,480 --> 00:07:35,290
Tarasov was the father
of the Soviet system.

41
00:07:35,350 --> 00:07:36,350
<i>Great!{\i}</i>

42
00:07:36,420 --> 00:07:37,920
And the head coach of the Red Army.

43
00:07:37,990 --> 00:07:40,690
<i>You'll become great hockey players!{\i}</i>

44
00:07:40,760 --> 00:07:43,500
<i>And great men!{\i}</i>

45
00:07:43,560 --> 00:07:47,840
This man played a big role in my life.

46
00:07:47,900 --> 00:07:49,640
I was Red Army in my heart.

47
00:07:49,650 --> 00:07:52,150
I came there. I was 10 years old.

48
00:07:52,150 --> 00:07:56,340
Tarasov, he developed the program.

49
00:07:56,400 --> 00:08:00,220
He wrote a few books about hockey.

50
00:08:00,270 --> 00:08:04,830
These books laid next to my
bed since I was a little kid.

51
00:08:06,630 --> 00:08:10,620
He described the game in a very simple way.

52
00:09:03,800 --> 00:09:06,690
Our training camps were together.

53
00:09:06,690 --> 00:09:10,860
My chess team and the national hockey team.

54
00:09:15,650 --> 00:09:17,700
They would often come to me

55
00:09:17,700 --> 00:09:21,730
if they had questions
on psychological training.

56
00:09:28,460 --> 00:09:32,800
He studied the training of the Bolshoi,

57
00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:36,970
and he applied it to hockey.

58
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:40,650
<i>Look at these dances, eh?{\i}</i>

59
00:09:40,710 --> 00:09:42,720
<i>It's like the boogie woogie!{\i}</i>

60
00:09:46,950 --> 00:09:49,760
Sport is an art form.

61
00:09:49,820 --> 00:09:51,630
That's what Tarasov thought.

62
00:09:54,060 --> 00:09:56,800
Creativity, a vivid mind, and constant

63
00:09:56,780 --> 00:10:01,330
thinking are needed for greatness.

64
00:10:06,170 --> 00:10:08,510
My father was not just a hockey coach...

65
00:10:10,920 --> 00:10:14,950
he was a great mentor.

66
00:10:15,010 --> 00:10:19,520
He could see the potential
in a young person.

67
00:10:21,850 --> 00:10:24,490
He developed my patriotism.

68
00:10:24,550 --> 00:10:26,550
For us, it's very important.

69
00:10:26,620 --> 00:10:30,730
For me since I was ten, it was
very important what was in front.

70
00:10:30,790 --> 00:10:33,400
The name of my team, my country.

71
00:10:51,950 --> 00:10:54,290
I belong to the great nation.

72
00:10:54,350 --> 00:10:56,760
If you wear the national team uniform,

73
00:10:56,760 --> 00:10:58,330
that's your duty. To do your best.

74
00:10:58,390 --> 00:11:01,300
To represent your country.

75
00:12:09,160 --> 00:12:12,160
Have you ever watched hockey?

76
00:12:13,030 --> 00:12:15,790
<i>I like playing with dolls.{\i}</i>

77
00:12:16,060 --> 00:12:19,410
Do you know what these letters mean:

78
00:12:19,470 --> 00:12:22,310
K-G-B?

79
00:12:22,370 --> 00:12:24,110
<i>No.{\i}</i>

80
00:12:24,170 --> 00:12:26,380
Yeah, you were born much later.

81
00:12:26,440 --> 00:12:28,610
You didn't have to deal
with this organization.

82
00:12:48,500 --> 00:12:50,640
When we crossed the
Atlantic to play against

83
00:12:50,700 --> 00:12:54,870
the best Ontario clubs at 16 years old,
I was happy.

84
00:12:59,310 --> 00:13:01,380
There was one flight per week.

85
00:13:01,440 --> 00:13:04,150
Empty because nobody was flying.

86
00:13:04,210 --> 00:13:07,520
Of course, regular people cannot leave

87
00:13:07,580 --> 00:13:11,030
the country because that's the system.

88
00:13:11,010 --> 00:13:15,770
I used to go with them to provide security,

89
00:13:15,770 --> 00:13:21,150
and to prevent any "escapes" to the West.

90
00:13:22,260 --> 00:13:24,300
The "special people" who traveled with us,

91
00:13:24,370 --> 00:13:26,970
they give your passport before you
get to passport control,

92
00:13:27,030 --> 00:13:32,040
and they collect the passport
when you cross the border.

93
00:13:33,540 --> 00:13:37,080
The Canadians put us in a five-star hotel.

94
00:13:37,140 --> 00:13:38,790
Chandeliers. Marble.

95
00:13:38,790 --> 00:13:41,090
One room per player,

96
00:13:41,150 --> 00:13:42,550
and a hundred TV channels.

97
00:13:51,130 --> 00:13:54,160
Fruits, vegetables in the wintertime.

98
00:13:54,140 --> 00:13:57,070
I've never seen it before for us.

99
00:13:57,130 --> 00:14:00,480
In the Soviet Union,
we got fish only one day a week.

100
00:14:00,530 --> 00:14:03,210
It was "Fish Thursday."

101
00:14:03,190 --> 00:14:07,480
When people went abroad,
especially for the first time,

102
00:14:07,540 --> 00:14:11,790
they were so surprised by the differences.

103
00:14:12,310 --> 00:14:13,520
We got $48.

104
00:14:13,580 --> 00:14:17,120
They gave us pocket money.

105
00:14:17,120 --> 00:14:19,600
I bought 2 jeans, 3 pair of shorts.

106
00:14:19,650 --> 00:14:23,130
Lots of stuff which just didn't
exist in Moscow.

107
00:14:24,630 --> 00:14:28,870
However, they never saw

108
00:14:28,930 --> 00:14:33,810
the negative side of the other countries.

109
00:14:35,810 --> 00:14:38,280
Control was intense.

110
00:14:38,340 --> 00:14:42,690
Without such intense control, there
was no point in the work at all.

111
00:14:44,480 --> 00:14:49,390
I was never even thinking about to defect.

112
00:14:49,450 --> 00:14:53,300
Never. What's that mean?

113
00:14:54,820 --> 00:14:56,670
I'm happy.

114
00:15:07,330 --> 00:15:10,590
The building was 12,000 people. Packed.

115
00:15:11,610 --> 00:15:14,380
I was so nervous, y'know?

116
00:15:14,390 --> 00:15:16,080
We got shitty gear.

117
00:15:36,160 --> 00:15:37,670
We beat them in all 5 games.

118
00:16:16,740 --> 00:16:18,510
<i>Which players do you like the best?{\i}</i>

119
00:16:28,180 --> 00:16:33,790
Okay, Gabe. Let's go. Let's go. Work!

120
00:16:33,890 --> 00:16:38,060
You guys are used to doing
nothing over there in America.

121
00:17:16,300 --> 00:17:18,280
Tarasov disagreed and stopped the game.

122
00:17:18,330 --> 00:17:20,740
We didn't play for 40 minutes.

123
00:17:20,720 --> 00:17:22,560
And there sat Brezhnev.

124
00:17:24,570 --> 00:17:27,190
And Brezhnev was saying,
"What the hell is this?"

125
00:17:30,940 --> 00:17:34,400
They removed him from the national team.

126
00:17:34,820 --> 00:17:36,990
They punished him for this.

127
00:17:39,950 --> 00:17:44,130
The KGB Chief was a fan
of the Red Army Club.

128
00:17:45,190 --> 00:17:47,170
Tikhonov was his protégé.

129
00:17:55,800 --> 00:17:57,080
What do you mean powerful?

130
00:17:58,270 --> 00:18:00,050
What do you mean powerful?
He's a part of the system.

131
00:18:00,050 --> 00:18:03,890
The Chief of the KGB put
him in the position.

132
00:18:09,050 --> 00:18:12,030
If we didn't obey,
he would punish us severely.

133
00:18:14,890 --> 00:18:16,900
He would take your salary
or bar you from playing.

134
00:18:48,460 --> 00:18:50,530
<i>I'm very volatile.{\i}</i>

135
00:18:50,590 --> 00:18:55,730
<i>That's how I am.{\i}</i>

136
00:18:55,800 --> 00:18:58,940
<i>And the guys know that.{\i}</i>

137
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:02,880
<i>They know when to approach me.{\i}</i>

138
00:19:04,940 --> 00:19:08,550
Tikhonov was in a very advanced
position from the beginning.

139
00:19:08,610 --> 00:19:11,180
He got the best team in the world.

140
00:19:11,250 --> 00:19:14,190
He got all kinds of support
from the government.

141
00:19:14,250 --> 00:19:18,530
In the Soviet Union, you
can get any player.

142
00:19:18,590 --> 00:19:23,300
You draft him into the army
and he becomes a Red Army player.

143
00:19:24,960 --> 00:19:29,170
Can Tikhonov be successful without us?

144
00:19:29,230 --> 00:19:31,570
I don't know.

145
00:19:31,630 --> 00:19:35,910
We being successful without him?

146
00:19:35,970 --> 00:19:38,710
I think so.

147
00:23:38,650 --> 00:23:40,560
<i>Destiny.{\i}</i>

148
00:24:09,140 --> 00:24:10,620
It was tough.

149
00:24:33,730 --> 00:24:36,340
After the Olympic games,

150
00:24:36,400 --> 00:24:40,040
Tikhonov fired the veterans.

151
00:24:41,810 --> 00:24:42,960
It's wrong.

152
00:24:44,040 --> 00:24:46,460
All these guys, all these supporting staff,

153
00:24:46,510 --> 00:24:48,360
this is the successful team.

154
00:24:48,420 --> 00:24:50,050
Not him.

155
00:24:53,250 --> 00:24:56,340
After that game,
the workload became tremendous.

156
00:24:56,340 --> 00:24:58,430
There were players who pissed blood.

157
00:25:03,400 --> 00:25:05,970
We practiced four times a day
in the summertime.

158
00:25:06,030 --> 00:25:07,380
Four times.

159
00:25:07,430 --> 00:25:09,740
We're working at a heart rate of 220.

160
00:25:09,800 --> 00:25:11,510
Can you imagine? 220.

161
00:25:30,890 --> 00:25:36,430
<i>You win by being merciless in training.{\i}</i>

162
00:25:36,500 --> 00:25:42,450
<i>The coach must perpetuate this tradition.{\i}</i>

163
00:25:43,430 --> 00:25:47,610
A coach must find a player's pressure

164
00:25:47,670 --> 00:25:51,480
points to achieve maximum results.

165
00:25:55,400 --> 00:26:00,580
It's the carrot and the stick,
like an animal trainer.

166
00:26:00,580 --> 00:26:05,160
To get masterpieces from the beasts,

167
00:26:05,160 --> 00:26:08,420
you have to force them a little bit.

168
00:26:30,650 --> 00:26:33,600
Did I respect him?

169
00:26:33,650 --> 00:26:36,100
As my coach? Yes.

170
00:26:36,160 --> 00:26:38,930
As a person? No.

171
00:26:59,650 --> 00:27:01,720
You have to be born a goalie.

172
00:27:01,720 --> 00:27:03,450
I am a destroyer.

173
00:27:05,470 --> 00:27:09,690
I destroy the plans of the adversary.

174
00:27:10,120 --> 00:27:12,190
<i>Vladislav Tretiak in the net.{\i}</i>

175
00:27:12,190 --> 00:27:14,440
<i>The best goalie in the world.{\i}</i>

176
00:27:14,440 --> 00:27:16,730
<i>Tretiak is almost unbeatable.{\i}</i>

177
00:27:16,800 --> 00:27:20,640
The greatest goaltender
the game has ever seen.

178
00:27:20,700 --> 00:27:26,050
Tikhonov was given ready-to-use material.

179
00:27:26,110 --> 00:27:28,160
Tarasov had created stars.

180
00:27:28,710 --> 00:27:31,150
It was to his credit that
he created a five-man unit.

181
00:27:31,240 --> 00:27:33,090
They were the best.

182
00:27:40,650 --> 00:27:43,510
<i>...are the strike force of the Soviet team.{\i}</i>

183
00:27:43,510 --> 00:27:45,760
When the five got together,
no one knew how to play them.

184
00:27:52,270 --> 00:27:54,500
He was the most dangerous
player in the world.

185
00:28:01,110 --> 00:28:03,590
He can make the goal from nowhere, anytime.

186
00:28:03,640 --> 00:28:06,450
He scored more goals than
anybody in our hockey history.

187
00:28:15,580 --> 00:28:17,860
He was a Russian tank.

188
00:28:26,300 --> 00:28:29,140
He was the soul of the five-man unit.

189
00:28:36,010 --> 00:28:37,110
Igor was the professor.

190
00:28:39,950 --> 00:28:42,690
Because he was skinny like that.

191
00:28:42,750 --> 00:28:45,240
Not a professor, maybe nerd.

192
00:28:47,220 --> 00:28:48,890
Skinny but tough.

193
00:28:49,420 --> 00:28:51,000
It kind of misleads lots of guys.

194
00:29:00,870 --> 00:29:03,070
He was my best friend.

195
00:29:17,280 --> 00:29:19,790
He was teammate. He was roommate.

196
00:29:21,120 --> 00:29:24,530
Alex became my younger brother.

197
00:29:25,290 --> 00:29:26,860
My mom cooked for him,

198
00:29:26,930 --> 00:29:30,790
and my grandpa was like his grandpa.

199
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:37,000
It's tough to find any closer relationship
between two men.

200
00:29:39,810 --> 00:29:43,780
Alex is probably the best all-around
defenseman ever to play the game.

201
00:29:43,840 --> 00:29:48,620
I believe he (Slava) was the best
defenseman in the history of world hockey.

202
00:29:52,970 --> 00:29:54,980
Slava was our leader, of course.

203
00:29:55,720 --> 00:29:57,480
In the way he skated, his character.

204
00:30:08,100 --> 00:30:11,210
Tikhonov came from the Politburo and said:

205
00:30:11,270 --> 00:30:15,050
"Slava, I got good news.

206
00:30:15,110 --> 00:30:18,670
"You're going to be captain of
the Soviet National Team."

207
00:30:18,880 --> 00:30:20,880
I said, "Thank you, but I'm not."

208
00:30:22,050 --> 00:30:23,880
He said, "You stupid?"

209
00:30:24,920 --> 00:30:27,360
I said, "I'm not."

210
00:30:27,890 --> 00:30:30,130
But when I talked to the guys,

211
00:30:30,190 --> 00:30:32,430
they said, "We want you to be our captain."

212
00:30:34,230 --> 00:30:35,600
I said, "Okay."

213
00:30:36,930 --> 00:30:38,910
Why they choose me, I don't know.

214
00:30:38,970 --> 00:30:42,020
But I become the youngest ever
captain of the national team.

215
00:30:59,450 --> 00:31:05,430
We were great friends in real life.

216
00:31:06,490 --> 00:31:11,800
I tell you, they were good people,
kind and always ready to help.

217
00:31:13,170 --> 00:31:16,270
We never let each other down.

218
00:31:22,410 --> 00:31:24,690
We were all practically the same, you know?

219
00:31:25,850 --> 00:31:28,900
We'd celebrate the birthdays,
the family things.

220
00:31:28,900 --> 00:31:34,160
We went to restaurants together.
We would spend vacation time.

221
00:31:34,220 --> 00:31:36,430
We were all the same.

222
00:31:39,990 --> 00:31:43,290
We were the same.

223
00:31:43,800 --> 00:31:47,510
Why are you asking me the same thing?

224
00:32:07,590 --> 00:32:10,730
Sometimes you feel without a look.

225
00:32:10,790 --> 00:32:12,030
Your partner must be there.

226
00:32:19,160 --> 00:32:21,370
Fetisov was number two in scoring,

227
00:32:21,370 --> 00:32:24,640
even though he was a defender.

228
00:32:24,700 --> 00:32:27,670
He would go forward
and Makarov would draw back.

229
00:32:29,960 --> 00:32:31,780
Everything was like this.

230
00:32:31,840 --> 00:32:35,190
The opponents did not know who to cover.

231
00:32:52,320 --> 00:32:54,970
No one could hold them back.

232
00:32:54,950 --> 00:32:57,450
What they did on the ice...

233
00:32:58,490 --> 00:33:00,450
Yes, they were the best.

234
00:34:57,260 --> 00:34:59,790
It was the greatest moment in my life.

235
00:34:59,860 --> 00:35:02,200
My childhood dream come true.

236
00:35:02,200 --> 00:35:03,910
I got this gold medal.

237
00:35:06,200 --> 00:35:09,770
I was the happiest man in the world.

238
00:35:23,250 --> 00:35:28,100
My brother, his name was Anatoly.

239
00:35:30,390 --> 00:35:36,340
I think he would be one of the
best forwards ever to play the game.

240
00:35:38,800 --> 00:35:40,710
He was like a son to me.

241
00:35:40,770 --> 00:35:44,540
We got almost 10 years apart.

242
00:35:47,010 --> 00:35:52,120
He was killed in a car accident in 1985.

243
00:35:55,350 --> 00:35:58,260
I was driving the car.

244
00:36:13,030 --> 00:36:17,480
To be in a situation like that,

245
00:36:17,540 --> 00:36:21,740
I didn't want to live.

246
00:36:21,940 --> 00:36:26,980
<i>I share everything they go through.{\i}</i>

247
00:36:27,050 --> 00:36:31,460
<i>All the training, all happiness and sadness.{\i}</i>

248
00:36:31,520 --> 00:36:35,430
<i>Losses and victories, all the positive,{\i}</i>

249
00:36:35,490 --> 00:36:39,050
<i>and the negative, too.{\i}</i>

250
00:36:39,530 --> 00:36:43,910
Andrei Khomutov found out
his father was going to die soon.

251
00:36:43,960 --> 00:36:45,670
He came to him and said,

252
00:36:45,730 --> 00:36:48,810
"Viktor, can you let me
go to see my father?"

253
00:36:50,100 --> 00:36:52,080
He said, "No.

254
00:36:52,140 --> 00:36:54,520
"You have to get ready for the next game."

255
00:36:56,240 --> 00:36:58,650
Andrei never saw his father again.

256
